description:
A collection of short stories, gathers the tales of Ryan Andrews into one volume. In these pages an elderly couple finds themselves the proud parents of a seed. Three brothers, afraid of revenge, afraid of revenge seeking zombie geese, take it among themselves to properly bury a fallen flock. Peculiar creatures reside beneath the trees of an old forest. And a dark mysterious tunnel beckons you in for a closer look.

This book contains four stories. Two of the comics, Sarah and the Seed, and Our Blood Stained Roof have been honored with an Eisner Award nominations in the Best Digital Comic category. The other two stories are: The Tunnel and Nothing is Forgotten.

Second cover is of the second edition that came out in july 2014.

A collection of short comics and comic strips made by over 40 artists. For all ages, but especially aimed at a very young audience. The comic is available for free on-line at Moose Kid Comics.

A very limited edition of 200 printed copies were made.

Frank Doberman rejoins the police force after years of exile, but instead of being top dog like in the old days, he finds hims himself starting over with a new uniform, new rules and regulations and a new partner.

The prequel to the upcoming graphic novel Pantheon, The Heavenly Cow sets up the universe in which the Egyptian myths takes place. Featuring Ra, Hathor, Nut and Anubis, all characters who play minor roles in the full book!

Available as digital and paper comic.

Frank is, as everyone knows, Jim Woodring's bestselling cartoon character. Jim, on the other hand, is Woodring's cartoon alter ego, the fictional doppelganger who has for 30 years inhabited Woodring's alternate universe where shifting, phantasmagoric landscapes, abrupt, hallucinatory visual revelations, and unexpected eruptions of uninhibited verbal self-flagellation are common- place. Jim is a mind-bending collection of all of Woodring's best non-Frank creative work comics stories, prose stories, drawings, and paintings, with a new introduction and afterword by the man himself. Abounding in metaphors if you choose to see them and naked self-disclosure if you don't, this volume of comics, prose, and images collected here for the first time is a bounty of Woodring's inspired artistry.
name: HC

description:
"Revenant", introduces and follows the Vampire Guardian Angels' future leader, Janos, who does not realize he is a reincarnated Vampire Guardian Angel, the son of Gregory, an ancient Vampire Guardian Angel, and the Vampire Countess Elizabeth Bathory. Janos is stalked by Gregory who tries to convince his son that his destiny is to become the leader of the Vampire Guardian Angels.

Based ont he vampire novel 'The Guardian' by Lia Scott Price.

description:
"Dominion", focuses on the origins of the Vampire Guardian Angels and their existence in the Bible. They were hidden by the Church, who fed sinners to them. An author discovers this secret through her research. The three vengeful angels, wanting dominion over man, go on a killing spree as they wait for the vampire invasion of Heaven and for the coming of their new leader. The Author, a Detective, and the Guardian Angel Cameron, now a Vampire, work to stop them.

Based on the Vampire Trilogy novel "Dominion" by Lia Scott Price.
name: Dominion

description: The long anticipated reprint of the entire run of Lee Falk and Ray Moore's The Phantom full-color Sundays begins! Fans of The Ghost Who Walks have waited for years to have a complete series of full size hardcover volumes featuring the complete Phantom Sundays. Presented in Volume One are the first eight storylines of the strips which encompass the first continuity, "The League of Lost Men" (May 28-October 15, 1939) to "Castle in the Clouds" (October 18, 1942-April 18, 1943). In addition to the strips, this volume contains documentary materials and a detailed essay. Don't miss it!
name: Volume One: 1939-1943

description: CANNONS IN THE CLOUDS follows the adventures of Sela Windbourne, a spunky teenage girl with her head in the clouds, literally. Sela lives in a world of floating islands, the surviving fragments of a once-powerful lost civilization, where she dreams of escaping the rigid rules of her aristocratic upbringing. When she finds herself on the run from a bloodthirsty conspiracy, her course collides with a young steeplejack named Robb Cadman. While Robb lacks Selas wealth or influence, he possesses an uncanny connection with diametal, the mysterious substance that powers flying ships and fuels their entire civilization. As they try to unravel the true motives of their pursuers, the pair must join forces with unlikely allies - a crew of pirates captained by the notorious Jenny Avery - to keep their world from crashing down.

The New York Times bestselling novel now adapted into comics, featuring full-color illustrations by Hugo Award-nominated artist Jimmy Broxton, and as adapted by fan-favorite writers Jimmy Palmiotti and Justin Gray. This contemporary dystopian classic--hailed by Justin Cronin, New York Times bestselling author of The Passage, as "an epic feat of imagination"--will captivate readers both familiar and new. This is the story of mankind clawing for survival, of mankind on the edge. The world outside has grown unkind, the view of it limited, talk of it forbidden. But there are always those who hope, who dream. These are the dangerous people, the residents who infect others with their optimism. Their punishment is simple. They are given the very thing they profess to want: They are allowed outside. In issue #6 of 6: The conclusion! From the shadows of annihilation strides a warrior for liberation...
name: Homecoming

In this second issue Jontar travels to the dream dimension 'Temple Island' to investigate if the elf he found in a trashcan is related to the golden elf statues on the island.
